Q1. [5 points] What is the mode of 'quality'? ¶

In [19]:

The mode of quality is: 5

The mode (most commonly occuring value) of the wine quality value is 5. There was only one mode reported in the stats.mode() results, indicating that this is likely not a multimodal distribution.

Q4. [15 points] Calculate the standard deviation and 95% confidence interval (i.e. the range between the 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles) of "fixed acidity". Use these values to determine to what extent the distribution of "fixed acidity" conforms to the empirical rule (i.e. that 95% of the values fall within 2 standard deviations of the mean). ¶

In [89]:
fixed_acidity_ci = (np.percentile(wine['fixed acidity'],2.5), np.percentile(wine['fixed acidity'],97.5))
fixed_acidity_mean = np.mean(wine['fixed acidity'])
fixed_acidity_std = np.std(wine["fixed acidity"])
two_stdev_fixed_acidity = ((fixed_acidity_mean - (2 * fixed_acidity_std)),(fixed_acidity_mean + (2 * fixed_acidity_std)))

print(f"95% confidence interval: {fixed_acidity_ci}")
print(f"Two standard deviations above and below the mean: {two_stdev_fixed_acidity}")

95% confidence interval: (5.6, 12.5)
Two standard deviations above and below the mean: (4.838533673075281, 11.800740873516395)

The distribution of fixed aciditiy does not conform neatly to the empirical rule. Two standard deviations towards the upward bound lies within the 95% confidence interval, but the lower bound is problematic. Two standard deviations negative of the mean puts the value outside of the confidence interval, which indicates that the estimate of the true population mean may be incorrect given this sample.

Q6. [10 points] Create the following plot: ¶

Provide a meaningful interpretation of the plot.

In [95]:
sns.violinplot(wine["quality"],wine["pH"], hue = wine["is_sweet"], split = True)
Out[95]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x26c06f24f08>

This violin plot visualizes the differences in pH distributions at each quality level. Because the violin plots are split, we can see the differences between sweet and non sweet wines. The most striking change in the plot is the pH distribution of non sweet wines at quality rank 8. There is a wider range of acceptable pH values for non sweet wines at quality rank 8 whereas the pH distribution for sweet wines shrinks.

In general, pH distributions tend to cluster between 3.75 and 2.8 for both non sweet and sweet wines. For sweet wines there does not appear to be much variability in pH across quality levels, except for on the extremes (3 and 8). Non sweet wines, on the other hand, vary more greatly across quality levels.

Q7. [10 points] Create a pairplot that includes the following variables. Use color to differentiate "good" from "bad" wines, using the "is_good" column. ¶

  • 'fixed acidity',
  • 'volatile acidity',
  • 'citric acid',
  • 'residual sugar',
  • 'free sulfur dioxide',
  • 'pH',
  • 'alcohol'

Explain what trends do you notice in good wines? What about bad wines?

In [100]:
sns.pairplot(data = wine, hue = "is_good",vars = ["fixed acidity",
                                  "volatile acidity",
                                  "citric acid",
                                  "residual sugar", 
                                  "free sulfur dioxide",
                                  "pH",
                                  "alcohol"])
Out[100]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x26c103ea448>

For the most part, good and bad wines follow similar distributions. The biggest difference is when looking at alcohol values of good and bad wines. Good wines have a varying distribution of alcohol content whereas bad wines overwhelmingly cluster around 10% alcohol content. Citric acid has the next closest deviation in distribution with slightly lower values of citric acid being considered better wines. pH, residual sugar, and free sulfur dioxide do deviate from one another very much, indicating that the difference between good and bad is likely not determined by these factors. Bad wines, on the whole, tend to have excess in one or two factors, but by far the biggest differentiator in good or bad is alcohol content.

Q8. [10 points] Create a scatterplot of 'chlorides' (on the y-axis) vs. 'sulphates' (on the x-axis) and label one interesting point. Use appropriate text and positioning for your annotation. ¶

Explain why you selected that point.

In [108]:
sns.scatterplot(wine["sulphates"], wine["chlorides"])

plt.annotate('Potential Outlier', xy=(2, 0.6), xytext=(1.5, 0.5),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='red', shrink=0.05),
            )
plt.show()

I selected this point because it deviates greatly from the rest of the group. Points like this ought to be carefully examined. What happened here? Was there an error in measurement? Was this a bad batch of a particular wine? It's important to ask questions about outliers to determine whether or not we should keep them in our data when calculating statistics. A point like this will pull the mean upwards for both sulphates and chlorides and its effect will be exaggerated the smaller our dataset becomes.
